  "query": "In Mediterranean agricultural systems, what is the evidence for differences in soil and water outcomes between long-term and short-term use of cover crops?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence from Mediterranean agricultural systems, there are limited but specific findings regarding differences between long-term and short-term use of cover crops:\n\n**Soil Quality Outcomes**: One study from Spain found higher soil quality in plots with long-term cover crops compared to short-term (Action 1345). Additionally, one study from France found more organic matter in soils with permanent ground cover compared to temporary ground cover in one of three comparisons (Action 1367). The same French study found more phosphorus in soils with permanent ground cover compared to temporary ground cover in one of three comparisons, and more microbial biomass in soils with permanent ground cover compared to temporary ground cover in some comparisons (Action 1367). Another study from France found more nematodes in soils with permanent ground cover compared to temporary ground cover in one of three comparisons (Action 1367). One study from Italy found the least erosion with permanent cover crops and the most erosion with temporary cover crops (Action 1367).\n\n**Water Outcomes**: One study from Spain found more water in soils with long-term cover crops compared to short-term in some comparisons (Action 1357).\n\nThe evidence base is limited, with most comparative studies between long-term and short-term cover crops coming from individual studies in France, Spain, and Italy. The available evidence consistently suggests that long-term or permanent cover crops provide greater benefits for soil quality parameters including organic matter, nutrients, microbial biomass, soil organisms, and erosion control compared to short-term or temporary cover crops.",
