{"summary": "Several management practices can improve soil fertility on Mediterranean farmland without adding amendments like manure or slurry. Crop rotation practices are effective, particularly including legumes in rotations, as studies from Canada, Portugal and Zambia found increased numbers of microbes and diversity of soil animals (857). Four studies from Australia, Canada, and Denmark found increased soil organic carbon under crop rotation, particularly when legumes were included (857). Cover crops grown beneath main crops or between crop rows also improve soil fertility, with two controlled trials from India and South Africa finding increased soil organic matter under cover crops (897). One study from Spain found that cover crops increased bacterial numbers and activity (897).

Reduced tillage practices offer another approach, with twelve studies from Australia, Canada, China, Europe, Japan and the USA finding higher soil organic carbon in soils under no-tillage or reduced tillage systems compared to conventionally tilled soil (906). Eight studies from Canada, China, Europe, Morocco, and the USA found maintained or increased soil organic matter and improved soil structure under reduced tillage (906). Green manures provide additional benefits, with two controlled, randomized, replicated studies from India and Pakistan finding higher soil organic carbon when green manures were grown (908).

Agroforestry systems, including alley cropping with trees, resulted in higher diversity of arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi in a study from Canada (903). Intercropping practices also contribute to soil health, with trials showing increased earthworm abundance in maize plots followed by rye grass crops (124). These practices collectively provide alternatives to manure amendments for maintaining and improving Mediterranean soil fertility through biological and physical soil management approaches.", "action_ids": ["857","897","906","908","903","124"], "query": "Instead of adding amendments like manure or slurry, what other management practices can be used to improve soil fertility on Mediterranean farmland?"}

