{
  "query": "What are the overall effects of using no-tillage in arable fields in Mediterranean climates, covering crop yield, soil health, water availability, and pest numbers?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies from Mediterranean countries including Italy, Spain, Portugal, and Lebanon, no-tillage practices in arable fields show mixed effects across the key areas examined. \n\n**Crop Yield**: Studies show inconsistent results for crop yields under no-tillage systems. Eight studies from Italy and Spain found higher crop yields with no tillage compared to conventional tillage in some or all comparisons, while seven studies from Italy, Lebanon, Spain, and the USA found lower crop yields with no tillage in some or all comparisons. Four studies from Italy and Spain found inconsistent differences (sometimes higher, sometimes lower yields), and three studies from Italy, Portugal, and Spain found similar yields between systems (Action 1355).\n\n**Soil Health**: No-tillage generally improves soil health indicators. One meta-analysis of studies from Mediterranean countries found more organic matter in no-tillage soils compared to tilled soils. Fourteen studies from Italy, Spain, and the USA found more organic matter with no-tillage in some or all comparisons. Seven studies from Spain and the USA found that no-tillage soils were more stable than tilled soils in some or all comparisons. Five studies from Italy and Spain found more microbial biomass in no-tillage soils, and two studies from the USA found more earthworms in no-tillage soils (Action 1369).\n\n**Water Availability**: No-tillage predominantly improves water availability. Nine controlled studies from Spain and the USA found more water in no-tillage soils compared to tilled soils in some or all comparisons. Only one study from Lebanon found less water in no-tillage soils in some comparisons. One study from Spain found that barley used water more efficiently in no-tillage plots compared to tilled plots in some comparisons (Action 1384).\n\n**Pest Numbers**: No-tillage effects on pest numbers are mixed, with weeds being the primary concern. Three studies from Italy and Spain found more weeds in no-tillage plots compared to conventional tillage in some comparisons, while four studies from Italy, Spain, and the USA found inconsistent differences in weed numbers. One study from Italy found more weed species in no-tillage plots. However, one study from Italy found fewer parasitic plants (broomrapes) in no-tillage plots, and one study from Syria found no differences in most diseases between tillage systems (Action 1397).",
